<br />
You can&#39;t really find the PTA 1974 full act online from the government as they don&#39;t archive back on the net that far but some places that contain parts of it include University servers.  Basically I can&#39;t be bothered to write more out, and you lot probably wouldn&#39;t care if I did (I bet a lot of you are even thinking "Thank &#39;whatever deity you do/don&#39;t believe in here&#39; she&#39;s not writing any more!).  I tend to be very thorough when I decide to do some research into anything, I guess it comes from doing a degree in Molecular Biology, sorry and everything.  Just delete it all if you want - I&#39;m sure it&#39;s just cluttering up the boards. </TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>the-mental-1™</B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/freedomcon/buzz.php?ignorename=the-mental-1™'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">hey Cabbage, I think I looked at that for some of my rant source ;o) </TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#EFF1FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#EFF1FF><font class="bfont"><B>the-mental-1™</B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/freedomcon/buzz.php?ignorename=the-mental-1™'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#EFF1FF' ><font class="bfont">Neal, I knew you had the wrong film I also knew which film you meant, I live in the town that they were accused of bombing.  I do know that it is based on actual events, but I&#39;m pretty certain the film says just that "based on" which is the film company&#39;s way to say either &#39;we can&#39;t promise this is a completely truthful account&#39; (maybe they couldn&#39;t gather enough evidence to prove everything and people&#39;s accounts can vary) or &#39;we&#39;ve changed this a bit to make the movie that much more watchable&#39; depending on how you look at it.  I know a lot more about the history surrounding it because of that and because of my dad being in the army.  I grew up being told about things like checking the car before you get in it, making sure that you used a different route to the army base if you happened to be going onto camp for any reason and also varying your routine as much as possible so that you were less of a target.  Let&#39;s just say it&#39;s a unique way to grow up.<br />
<br />
The anti-terrorism laws were a terrible violation of the civil rights of anyone involved.  However, they did not allow legal beatings, the problem is that the PTA (Prevention of Terrorism Act) allowed the authorities to detain suspects for up to seven days without charge. It also gave the home secretary powers to exclude people from Britain to Northern Ireland,  pretty much an internal exile within the UK, if he &#39;reasonably believed&#39; them to be involved in terrorism, without needing to go to court or offer any evidence. <br />
<br />
It allowed the police to cordon off entire areas, to stop and search people they &#39;reasonably suspected&#39; might be terrorists, and to confiscate any items they suspected could be used for &#39;terrorist purposes&#39; (including, in some instances, black gloves, rope, building equipment and even A-Z maps). <br />
<br />
New Labour&#39;s Terrorism Act came into force in February 2001, superseding both the Prevention of Terrorism Act 1974 and the Northern Ireland Emergency Provisions Act 1973. The original PTA was passed in November 1974 - the last time a British government declared &#39;war on terrorism&#39;.  This occured in response to the IRA&#39;s Birmingham pub bombings that left 21 people dead.  Some people believe that the PTA was more about harassing Irish people than about&#39;preventing terrorism&#39; <br />
and state that it  undermined their civil liberties.  Then again I&#39;ve already mentioned that we in the UK have nothing like a constitution or a bill of rights... <br />
<br />
I&#39;ve done some research now and I think that around 7052 (mostly Irish) people were detained under the PTA between 1974 and 1991, only 14 percent had charges brought against them . Many of the other 6097 (86 percent) were held for days at a time, denied access to a solicitor, interrogated (without the safeguards that suspects today are promised in police custody), and then released again - left with the stigma of being an Irish person arrested on suspicion of being involved in terrorism.  I&#39;m not saying it&#39;s right, and the fact that they didn&#39;t have access to a lawyer/solicitor and other recourse to the courts certainly means that beatings or other forms of torture could easily have taken place.  Still, and I know I&#39;m repeating myself here, it never said "you can legally beat people up if you think they&#39;re terrorists" in any way, shape, or form. <br />
<br />
The new Terrorism Act within the UK seems to incorporate a lot of what was in the old PTA with different wording.  It also has a few added dimensions...The Terrorism Act defines terrorism as &#39;the use or threat of action designed to influence the government or to intimidate the public or a section of the public&#39;, which &#39;involves serious violence against a person&#39;, &#39;serious damage to property&#39;, &#39;endangers a person&#39;s life&#39;, &#39;creates a serious risk to the health or safety of the public&#39;, or &#39;is designed seriously to interfere with an electronic system&#39;.  This means it doesn&#39;t just deal with things like bombs but with the use of the internet, particularly hacking - or even something as simple as a political protest.<br />
<br />
If the police &#39;reasonably suspect&#39; that acts of terrorism are likely to be carried out, they can seek an &#39;authorisation&#39; to declare an area an &#39;emergency zone&#39; for up to 28 days. And within the emergency zone, rights go out the window. A police officer can &#39;arrest without a warrant a person whom he reasonably suspects to be a terrorist&#39;, &#39;may stop and search a person whom he reasonably suspects to be a terrorist&#39;, and &#39;can stop a vehicle, and may search the vehicle, the driver of the vehicle, any passenger in the vehicle, anything in or on the vehicle or carried by the driver or passenger&#39;. <br />
<br />
Of course it gets silly when you think that I&#39;ve had my ice skates confiscated at an airport (to be returned after my flight) and other passengers coming into and out ofrimbazel airports have had similar experiences with items as varied as nail scissors/clippers to tennis rackets, I have to wonder who gets to decide what "reasonable suspicions" can cover.  <br />
<br />
Under the Terrorism Act it is also a crime to &#39;fail to disclose&#39; information that might lead to the arrest of a terrorist. Under the PTA, a similar subsection led to journalists being arrested - including the makers of a documentary on Northern Ireland for the Channel 4 Dispatches series - for failing to disclose their sources. Added to which the Terrorism Act makes it an offence, not only to be a member of a list of proscribed organisations (14 Irish ones plus new, mostly Islamic ones), but also to support them financially or to be present at a meeting of three or more people if just *one* of those people is a member of a proscribed organisation.  This is both ludicrous (I for one wouldn&#39;t know if someone I&#39;m at a party at, for example, is a member of any of these proscribed groups) and likely to impinge on free speech, and probably on journalistic integrity - I know it&#39;s an issue to some of my friends who work in media related industries.<br />
<br />
